SIMPLE: phylactery
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Phylactery
<hw>Phy*lac"ter*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Phylacteries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE.
<ets>filateri</ets>, OF. <ets>filatire</ets>, <ets>filatiere</ets>, F.
<ets>phylact⟦egrave⟧re</ets>, L. <ets>phylacterium</ets>, Gr.
<grk>fylakth`rion</grk>, fr. <grk>fylakth`r</grk> a watcher, guard,
<grk>fyla`ssein</grk> to watch, guard. Cf. <er>Philatory</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Any charm or amulet worn as a preservative from danger
or disease.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small square box, made either of parchment or of
black calfskin, containing slips of parchment or vellum on which are
written the scriptural passages Exodus xiii. 2-10, and 11-17, Deut. vi.
4-9, 13-22. They are worn by Jews on the head and left arm, on week-day
mornings, during the time of prayer.</def> <rj><au>Schaff-Herzog
Encyc.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Among the primitive Christians, a case in which the
relics of the dead were inclosed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Phylactocarp</ent>⟦br⟧
